('155392688', 'applestore', 'United States', 'Mostly great.', 'The app is for the most part the best navigation system currently exist.\nTwo things that are missing or a lack: \n1. I like knowing the speed limit permitted in any of the roads I drive. Waze doesn\'t have this (yet), therefor I need to use my regular GPS to have that.\n2. In areas where there\'s no signal available Waze stops working, you\'ll still have the map and navigation but you won\'t be alarmed as well as you can\'t report on any hazard/traffic/cop. \nOther than these two things, I LOVE it and would highly recommend that to everyone.\nUpdate:\nWaze solved the first thing on my missing list!!! Yay! That\'s great. \n\nThere\'s appear to be another issue with Waze which turns me to google maps usually, is that it doesn\'t know where I\'m located when I go to search something/name of a business. With google maps it\'s perfect. \nEven though google bought Waze and I have the app I still would like to be able to do a search without it giving a completely different state.', '41622717', 'applestore', 'Germany', 'Very nice, but ...', 'The idea and the implementation is in principle not bad done. But there are a few things that are very annoying: -if the data connection changes, e.g. From WiFi to LTE, then listen to Waze completely with the communication, there are no more updates. - if you want to use Waze on several devices, then you have to allow full access to contacts, etc., as soon as you want to log on to the second device. Why? Apart from that, I could not successfully log on to my existing Waze account on my iPad. - if you choose as an audio output &quot;BT-Telefongespräch&quot;, then this connection is established quite often (radio interrupts and switches to BT), but there is neither hinweison nor announcement.', 'Waze', 0.220302, 2, 0, 1, 1, '2017-03-26 00:40:02', 'long', 404, 0, -1, 0.875, 'ot', 'br'),
